description:
A scrappy expanse of silky refuges and capture webs littered with body parts of previous victims. When preferred prey is entangled, the female spiders emerge from their 'nests' and overpower it by grabbing its extremities. In this case, a wasp https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9319446. 
Presumably they inject venom because after a minute or so the prey stops struggling. Then they snip it out of the web and carry it into one of several 'nests' or refuges.
 Unwanted prey, often beetles (see https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9319435 ) are also killed but sometimes left in the web, uneaten.  Ants, in this case, Maranoplus ( https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9319390 )scavenge around the periphery of the webs, feasting on unwanted beetles or other left-overs.

About 3 - 3.2mm
Scavenging on what looks like a beetle carcas left on the periphery of a community spider web. Stegodyphus dumicola https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/9319352

7 part photostory, this one is for the fly
Photo 1:
 I Thought It Was A Yellowjacket
When I came inside my house, what I thought was a yellow jacket came in with me.  This is a problem because I like to go barefoot and I have cats that could get stung also.  I went to get a broom to try to slap it down out of the air.  When I came back it had gone to a window with blinds.  I discovered that a tiny spider had solved my problem.  The "yellow jacket" had been caught in a web.  Later when I got the insect identified by experts, it turned out to be a fly pretending to be a yellow jacket.  This is an example of Batesian mimicry which is when a harmless, tasty species mimics another species that is toxic or foul tasting or dangerous in order to be protected from predators.  Sure fooled me.  It did not deter the spider.
Photo 2:
Spider To The Rescue
The spider solved my problem.  Here is the spider coming to take a look at what it caught in its web.  I was shooting these photos through open blinds.
Photo 3:
Underside Of The Spider
I took this shot to help with getting an id on the spider.
Photo 4:
Topside Of The Spider
As the spider wrapped some silk around the fly's legs, I got a shot of the top side of the spider. 
Photo 5:
Uncropped Shot For Perspective
I left this shot uncropped to show how I was having to do this, shooting between two blinds slats.     
Photo 6:
Spider Injects venom
The spider may have been fooled by the mimicry because it avoided the end of the fly where a stinger would be if it were a wasp.  What the spider did, as shown here, was to bite the leg which injected venom.  The fly stopped struggling shortly after that.
Photo 7:
The Spider Won
I had to leave at this point so took this last photo of the spider.  Several hours later when I got back the fly was wrapped up in silk for a later meal.  The next morning there was nothing left to be seen.
Fly  id confirmed in bugguide here:  https://bugguide.net/node/view/1616641

This hawk was feeding on a ground squirrel in the shadows. I walked right by and would have missed it if it hadn't jumped out behind me.  When I heard the noise and turned around it was maybe 10 feet from me, but I guess didn't want to give up the rest of its meal. I took a step or two back and it walked over and continued feeding. Note the bit of squirrel meat visible in its bill in photo 4.

I returned about 90 min. later and took some pictures of the remains of the prey animal listed here:

Our San Jose pest controller Sneakers the Cat with a "bushy-tailed tree rat".  Eastern Gray Squirrels and Fox Squirrels have been introduced to many park areas in many large cities, and their populations have spread to the rural areas around those cities. These squirrels are tolerant of human activity, and even thrive in crowded urban and suburban environments. They exploit human habitations for sources of food and nesting sites, and are considered as "pests" in many areas, including my old San Jose backyard. 
Sneakers did NOT like eating the rats or mice that he caught, but this young Eastern Gray Squirrel was an exception, especially after I skinned and cooked it on the backyard Bar-B-Que grill for him, our dog Pepper, and myself. It was about time that my cat "fed" me a bit .........

Note the Mouse in Bobcat's mouth. Mouse killed and eaten about two minutes after the first photo. 
Initially, I was just taking photos of the Bobcat and didn't even realize that it had the mouse in its mouth until I reviewed the first photos on my camera after it had eaten the mouse, and was sitting next to the oak tree and looking "satisfied". The Sun had set behind the hill and I was in the canyon bottom, and using my telephoto lens in the "low" light resulted in the washed-out color. I estimated the Bobcat to be about 40 yards or so away.

I’d been watching my woods because of the dead opossum [ https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/150086636 ] I’d moved there.  Nothing amiss when walking out there 3/6/2023.  Morning of 3/7, from my window I saw red among the brown leaves.  With binos, I saw a big streak of bright red blood and a rib cage, then a coyote carrying something out of my sight.  The red blood had completely faded away within a half hour, which indicated to me the kill had been relatively recent.  Morning of 3/8, I ventured out and found where a young deer had been taken apart all over the place and (presumably) other creatures had been picking it clean.  My guess is that coyote(s) had pounced on the deer where it had bedded down for the night.  The dead opossum was untouched.
Lousy coyote photos provided only to provide proof of presence for Who eats Whom project.  White puddle visible just beyond the tail is the large quantity of white fur at the deer kill site.

https://subsites.wur.nl/upload_mm/e/e/8/be98b401-0126-4123-b8e2-65f7c7865f15_extra-info-granen.pdf

The spikelets bear up to twelve florets, mostly with a single glume, with only the terminal floret having two. The glumes are up to three-quarters the length of the spikelet; their outer surface is finely ribbed with longitudinal veins. There is no awn, the lemma is oblong and has five nerves and the palea is a similar shape with two nerve and a few fine hairs. The three anthers are yellow.
https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lolium_rigidum

Description

L. rigidum is an annual species forming open tussocks. The dominant habit is erect, but the species is variable in habit, ranging from dense prostrate to more open erect types. Geniculate stems, fibrous root system, up to 1 m high. Reddish-purple colouration at base of stems extends upwards as the plant matures. Leaf blades dark green, hairless, flat, upper surface evenly ribbed, lower surface smooth and shiny, 5-25 cm long, 3-5 mm wide. Young leaves rolled in bud. Auricles small and narrow. Ligule, white, translucent, shorter than wide. Leaf sheath hairless, with fine longitudinal ribs as in leaf blades, reddish-purple at base. Inflorescence is a spike up to 30 cm in length; spikelets edge on to the rachis. Rachis is recessed opposite each spikelet, which more or less fits into the recess. Spikelets of 10-12 florets, laterally flattened, green, 10-25 mm long. Only the terminal spikelet has two more or less equal glumes. Otherwise only one glume subtending each spikelet, lanceloate, 10-15 mm long, two-thirds to three-quarters as long as the spikelet, outer surface fine-veined, ribbed like the upper surface of the leaf blade. No awn. Lemma lanceolate, about 5 mm long, five nerved, usually with no awn, but terminal awns occasionally found, probably as a result of hybridization. Palea similar to lemma in shape and size, two nerves with tiny hairs along them. Anthers three, yellow.

Systematik
Erstmals systematisch beschrieben wurde die Bambusmilbe 1917 unter dem lateinischen Namen Stigmaeopsis celarius. 1950 wurde die Art neu beschrieben und der Gattung Schizotetranychus angegliedert. Dementsprechend wird man unter den Artnamen Schizotetranychus celarius die meiste Literatur finden. Vor kurzem allerdings wurde die Gattung Stigmaeopsis – aufgrund detaillierter molekularbiologischer und morphologischer Studien – wieder allein gestellt (Saito et al., 2004). Unterdessen konnten 7 Arten beschrieben werden, Stigmaeopsis celarius, Stigmaeopsis longus, Stigmaeopsis miscanthi, Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis, Stigmaeopsis tenuinidus, Stigmaeopsis sahara und Stigmaeopsis takahashii, von denen 6 auch tatsächlich an Bambus parasitieren. Nach einer vorläufigen Bestimmung durch Prof. Yutaka Saito (Hokkaido University, Japan) scheint es sich bei der in Deutschland verbreiteten Milbe um Stigmaeopsis longus oder Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis zu handeln (Prof. Saito, persönliche Mitteilung). Wahrscheinlich handelt es sich um Stigmaeopsis longus, da v.a. ältere Blätter befallen werden und Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis dafür bekannt ist, – zu mindest in China – junge Moso-Blätter im zeitigen Frühjahr zu befallen und zu schädigen.

the variation in nest size of the eight species corresponded well with the variation in dorsal seta sc1 length, suggesting that nest size variation among species may have a genetic basis. The time spent within a nest (nest duration) increased with nest size on the respective host plants. Nest arrangement patterns varied among species showing different sized nests: Large nest builders continuously extended their nests, while middle and small nest-building species built new separate nests, which resulted in different social interaction times among species, and is thought to be closely related to social development. Fecal deposition behaviors also varied among Stigmaeopsis species, suggesting diversity in anti-predatory adaptations.

Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis (Acari: Tetranychidae) has recently been found on bamboo species (Phyllostachys sp., P. viridiglaucescens, S. yashadake) in Alpes-maritimes, Hérault, Gard and Hérault departments. The first specimens had been collected in Gard in 2003 but were misidentified as S. celarius. Until recently, S. nanjingensis was only known to occur in China, but it has been found in Italy, Hungary and Portugal. The related species S. longus was first reported in the EPPO region in 2020 in the Netherlands (RS 2020/247), also introduced with bamboo plants.

So far, in Europe, two species of alien tetranychid 
mites have been recorded on bamboos, namely Stigmaeopsis celarius Banks in The Netherlands, Great 
Britain, Belgium and France, and Schizotetranychus 
bambusae Reck in France only (Vierbergen, 1997; 
Ostoja-Starzewski, 2000; Auger and Migeon, 2007). S. 
celarius is also widespread in the USA. 
Presently, the S. celarius complex consists of seven 
species: S. celarius, S. nanjingensis, S. longus (Saito), S. 
miscanthi (Saito), (the last two previously known as celarius in Japan), S. tenuinidis (Zhang et Zhang), S. saharai Saito et Mori and S. takahashi Saito et Mori, (Saito et al., 2004). Of these, only S. miscanthi inhabits plants other than bamboo.

Presently S. nanjingensis is widespread in the Veneto Region (North-Eastern Italy) on ornamental bamboos (Phyllostachys mitis, P. nigra and, to a less extent, Pseudosasa japonica). Infestations were observed in Padua, Treviso and Vicenza districts, both in new and old plantations of historical parks. Moreover it has been recorded also in the Liguria region (North-western Italy), at Ventimiglia (Imperia district), near the French border. The infested plants are easily recognizable by the whitish-yellow spots on the upper side of leaves.

So, jetzt habe ich mir doch mal den Volltext vorgenommen ;) :

Die 8 untersuchten Bambusmilbenarten der Gattung Stigmaeopsis unterscheiden sich unter anderem in der Art des Nestbaues und in der sozialen Organisation. Dabei treten zwei Extreme auf. Zum einem gibt es Arten, die – wie die bei uns eingescheppten Bambusmilben (Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis oder Stigmaeopsis longus) – große, aneinanderhängende Nester mit vielen Individuen bauen, welche beim Gegenangriff auf Räuber zusammenarbeiten können. Zum anderen gibt es Arten, die das Risiko eines Angriffs durch Räuber reduzieren, indem sie verstreut liegende kleine und feste Nester bauen, die nur mit größerem Aufwand aufgestöbert werden können und in welche die Räuber nur schlecht eindringen können. Die Individuen dieser Arten zeigen keinen Gegenangriff.



Daneben gibt es auch interessante Zwischen- bzw. Sonderformen des Nestbaus, auf die ich hier jedoch nicht näher eingehen möchte.



Interessant ist vielleicht noch, dass die Milben ihr Nest nicht mit ihren schlecht entwickelten Augen erkennen, sondern mithilfe bestimmter Borsten auf dem Rücken ertasten. Milbenarten mit größeren Borsten bauen auch größere Nester.



Insgesamt wurden 5 Arten der Kotablage beobachtet:
1. Ein einzelner Ablageplatz innerhalb des Nestes (Stigmaeopsis nanjingensis)
2. Ein einzelner Ablageplatz außerhalb des Nestes (Stigmaeopsis longus)
3. Zwei Ablageplätze außerhalb des Nestes
4. Mehrere Ablageplätze in unmittelbarer Nähe der Nestöffnungen
5. Weit entfernt von den Nestöffnungen wahllos verteilte Ablageplätze

description: Flower scarab - Valgus canaliculatus (males, ~5 mm) These were all over the persimmon flowers, often disappearing most of the way down into the flower. I have usually found them on Viburnum previously. These always remind me of ticks. Genus name is Latin valgus, "bow-legged". These are canaliculatus (versus V. seticollis), based on: - dark reddish brown (vs. piceous) - anterior tibiae with 3 slender, widely-separated teeth on outer side (vs. 5-6) - pronotum with many small teeth along edge (vs. large teeth) - overlapping cream-colored scales on abdominal sternites (vs. non-overlapping, tawny); visible in one image Female of canaliculatus has long process on pygidium, lacking here, so these should be males. It seems that primarily males visit flowers (Ratclifee and Paulsen). The species is termetophilous--eggs, larvae, and adults can be found in the galleries of Reticulitermes flavipes (several references below). References - BugGuide bugguide.net/node/view/5242 - Dillon and Dillon, A Manual of Common Beetles of Eastern North America (Row, Peterson, and Company, 1961), p. 558, plate 53(16) - Evans, Beetles of Eastern North America (Princeton University Press, 2014), p. 177 - Harpootlian, Scarab Beetles of South Carolina (Clemson University, 2001), p. 124, figs. 243, 285 - Ratcliffe and Jameson, Generic Guide to New World Scarabs unsm-ento.unl.edu/Guide/Scarabaeoidea/Scarabaeidae/Cetoni... - Ratcliffe and Paulsen, The Scarabaeoid Beetles of Nebraska (Bulletin of the University of Nebraska State Museum, Vol 22, 2008), pp. 503-4, fig. 688

This is the nicest looking wild pawpaw on the property. Seems to be a good combo of enough leaf litter (large oaks and magnolias nearby) and not too much shade. There is one larger than this at the edge of the forested area. It has the best soil but also the least light. It never seems to have any fruit. There are several other smaller ones in sunnier sandier areas. I have never gotten to try the fruit since animals always get them first. They are great for attracting Zebra Swallowtails though. Caterpillar on this bush: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/221016473

It's too expensive to water the garden enough for most vegetables with such sandy soil. Hence the container gardening. So this pawpaw is not getting any special treatment. It looked terrible during the severe drought last year (some wild bushes and trees died), but it bounced right back.

The nest box is about 3 ft high, so this snake must be at least 6 ft long. The box is about 20 ft above the ground on a 12-ft diameter pine. There was an owlet in the box the night before, never thought a snake could climb a tree like this. Thinking this might be a southern Timber Rattler, not sure what else would tangle with a big owl. It appears the snake got the owlet, then laid a trap or somehow tangled with one of the adults. Later photos showed what looked like an owl wing hanging from the box, with just one parent bird seen on a nearby branch. Then the wing was gone. Nothing at the box after May 22. Trying to id the snake if possible and complete a story here with just a few snapshots from the game camera.

Maybe a Pacific Staghorn Sculpin?

With Don Fraser; a visit to see what was around. The weather at 0943 was sunny and 68 degrees ("feels like" 66), with a light breeze, We made three stops. Alice Herden told me about the first stop; a recent burn with thousands of Liatris stalks. Unfortuntely, we did not see many native arthropods (but Western Honeybees were common). I don't think I had ever seen so many treefroggies (including many Pinewoods Treefrogs)!

These are my cell-phone images, which are GPS-enabled. In some cases, I am uploading a cell-phone image just to have the precise location, and I will later upload my (superior) camera images.

description: Sapsucker was enjoying the last few persimmons.

Most were sitting across rocks, all posed as if they had just died on the spot while walking along.

Apparently it's a fungus that emerges between the segments of a millipede usually 12 to 24 hours after rain.

Observation duplicated for the fungus here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/256022699

description:
An anemone devouring a rather large crab, listed here together with another photo:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/260195670

Does anyone know if these anemones can actually catch a crab, or is this just scavenging of a carcass that washed against it. I've seen this situation a few times, but I've also seen hermit crabs and small shore crabs walk right across the anemones unharmed.

A rock crab being consumed by an anemone, listed here together with another photo:
https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/260195669

A gull that was trying to eat a fish that might have been a bit too big to swallow. After watching it fail and drop it several times, I walked over to see what it was and took some pictures.
Listed here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/260195677

I don't know if the gull caught the fish or just found it. The gull walked back to continue trying after I retreated, and half an hour later the fish was gone. There had been some other gulls around, showing interest as well, so I don't know if it was swallowed whole, torn apart, or just carried off.

description: With Don Fraser, Clint Gibson, Shelley Rutkin, and Liz Childress; a successful chase of two rare bees. We found _Colletes banksi_ pollening on Dahoon Holly (_Ilex cassine_) -- a new food plant -- and we found several _Melissodes mitchelli_, the star of the show. According to Clint (who knows these things), mitchelli had not been identifiable photographed in the wild previously! It all started on 12 April 2025, when Don, Clint, and I participated in the Annuteliga Hammock butterfly count. During the count, I saw a bee gathering pollen from a prickly pear cactus. I took one cell-phone photograph then the bee was gone. Later, I showed Clint the photo, and he said that could be a real good bee, _Melissodes mitchelli_, which is a Florida endemic, is exclusive to prickly pear pollen ("oligolectic"), and is known from just a few records, all of them specimens. It turns out that Don had photographed probably the same bee last year at Chassahowitzka Wildlife and Environmental Area on a trip with me and Alice Herden. Then, Cliff and his wife found and collected a male _Melissodes mitchelli_ (Clint has permits ...) at Starkey Wilderness Preserve on 17 April 2025. So the stage was set for this day at Chassahowitzka. Clint found and captured (but did not collect) a _Melissodes mitchelli_, which we all photographed before Clint released it. We started out on Rattlesnake Camp Road and then drove Scrub Island Road. Finally, we drove 3 Bridge Road to the sandhills area at the northern edge of the property. I took my first photographs at 1055 and my last at 1539. The weather at the start was sunny, 84 degrees ("feels like" 85), and with SW winds at 9 MPH.
place_guess: Florida, Hernando, Chassahowitzka Wildlife and Environmental Area

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/19QeK74z6v/

Another elegant Assassin 🙂

We recently came across other Assassin Bugs that looked somewhat similar to this one here (a light-coloured one): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/282814263, and here (a dark-coloured one): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/282812233

It looks as if this is possibly a Vadimon sp.: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/642553-Vadimon and similar to Vadimon cf. bergrothi: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/694994-Vadimon-bergrothi and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/694994-Vadimon-bergrothi/browse_photos.

As Andrew Schild pointed out, "This one looks like it may have a Tachinid egg attached to its body; it may not be long for this world... - the larva will likely start to feed on the Assassin. A number of Tachinids target Pentatomomorph Bugs (Pentatomomorpha)." 😕 That certainly doesn't sound too great, but we have seen other insects in similar situations where things could still change, such as this moth: https://www.facebook.com/groups/Butterfliesandbugs/permalink/9081588435271909/?app=fbl. 

On the lookout in the bush in Gulu, on the outskirts of East London, Eastern Cape, South Africa 🇿🇦

Any idea what these caterpillars are? They were on this gorgeous wild-growing plant - possibly Commelina benghalensis (Bhengal dayflower/ tropical spiderwort/ Benghal wandering Jew): https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/76425-Commelina-benghalensis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/76425-Commelina-benghalensis/browse_photos.

Edit: According to Bertie le Roux these are Whitebar Acraea, Telchinia encedon caterpillars: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1482386-Telchinia-encedon, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1482386-Telchinia-encedon/browse_photos. Thanks Bertie! 🙂

It looks as if they are those of a Common Mimic Acraea, Telchinia encedon ssp. encedon: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1482671-Telchinia-encedon-encedon and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1482671-Telchinia-encedon-encedon/browse_photos.

Update1: An interesting development on these caterpillars - a few days after this initial post we found the parent butterfly laying eggs on the same plant - exactly the one that was suggested. Truly a beautiful story: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283285434 

Update2: Later had a chance to make some little videos of another wonderful batch of these caterpillars. You can see them here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283293338

Update3: We later found some of the butterflies in all their glory 😃 here 🧡: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283297366, here 🧡: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283299408 and here 🧡: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283197177.

Valeri noticed a small tiny grub on a fruit of a Litttleleaf Sensitive Briar (_Mimosa microphylla_) when she examined her photographs after arriving home. I went back today to get more photographs of the grub. And while I was there, I added 35 other new records, to put me over the 5,000-records mark for the iNaturalist project for Chassahowitzka. My first photograph was taken at 1049 and my last at 1133. I took no camera photographs. I forgot to record the weather, but it was sunny and close to 90 degrees ("feels like" temperature probably mid-90s), with a light breeze.

Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/15jghWWMNa/

A rather peculiar little thing we found on a Lantana flower.

It's about 7mm long.

It looks as if this might possibly be a Lantana Leaf Beetle, Octotoma scabripennis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/310775-Octotoma-scabripennis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/310775-Octotoma-scabripennis/browse_photos. Thanks for the ID confirmation Cameron Ramsey and Tony Rebelo! 🙂

"Octotoma scabripennis, known as the lantana leafminer and lantana leaf beetle, is a species of beetle in the family Chrysomelidae, originally from Central America and introduced into Australia to kill the previously invasive Lantana camara plant."

Interestingly enough this beetle was apparently also introduced here in South Africa, as one of many measures attempting to control invasive Lantana before 1997, according to this article by David Simelane, from the Agricultural Research Council (ARC): "Lantana camara (Verbenaceae)": https://www.arc.agric.za/arc-ppri/Pages/Lantana-camara.aspx.

According to this Fact Sheet from the Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry
Biosecurity Queensland in Australia: "Lantana Biocontrol, Octotoma scabripennis" (October 2013): https://www.daf.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/66458/IPA-Lantana-Biocontrol-3.pdf

"•  Octotoma scabripennis occurs naturally from Mexico to Nicaragua.
 •  Cultures of Octotoma scabripennis originated from Mexico.
 •  The insect was first released in Australia in 1966.
 •  Adults feed on the upper surfaces of leaves, leaving small scarification marks.
 •  Eggs are laid on the edge of adult feeding scars.
 •  Larvae feed in middle leaf layers, causing dark blotches.
 •  Pupation occurs in the leaves.
 •  Development from egg to adult takes 34–45 days.
 •  Adults live for 6–9 months, but may enter a period of inactivity during winter when conditions are unfavourable."

Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1AmLUPBfYS/

Despite our recent rather mixed caterpillar rearing experience: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285291566, in which our larger caterpillars ended up being parasitised by wasps, we still managed to find a few smaller caterpillars on our lettuces: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285277062, and we've decided to give it another go...

Here they are...very small (about 1.5cm), but two of the three have already pupated. Oddly enough, one has wrapped itself in some lettuce and the other has apparently decided to wrap itself inside the toilet tissue we put underneath to make the "floor" less cold.

Suncana Bradley previously identified these smaller caterpillars as potentially being the larvae of one of the lovely Crambid Snout Moths (Crambidae family): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285265884, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/52002-Crambidae and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=52002&view=species.

Here's to hoping they were too small to be stung! 

Update: Thankfully the little caterpillars all blossomed and became beautiful Rusty Dot Pearl moths: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/285342567. Thanks Suncana! You were right on the money! 💚🧡😄

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/16RA8BDi5Y/ 

Images part B of a 2 part observation - Part A here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286744979

The honey-choc Lady Beetles, AKA "Somethingeus deliciosus", apparently already has a name! 😄

A few months ago, in January, we came across some rather unusual hairy little honey-choc-coloured Lady Beetles. They were pupating on a Bugweed plant: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286740919.

We subsequently returned to see them again on the following day once their autumny colours had settled: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286741646. 

A few days later we found another one on our Lemon 🍋 tree: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286742671, and subsequently also on a Society Garlic Chive: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/286743766.

In the absence of an identity or name, at that stage, and inspired by the chocolatey grin on the backs of these little beetles, Jan Botha suggested "Somethingeus deliciosus" 😄🧡🤎

Since then, we've been seeing these beetles all over the place, until last week, when we came across this astonishing sight! 😮 Apparently the Somethingeous deliciosus beetles had found something even more delicious!

After one of our bush walks we happened to stroll past one of the many Yellow Bells plants in our area and we noticed that the honey-choc beetles, their eggs, larvae and pupae were all over the plant! What a surprise! 👀 We also found a pupa on a neighbouring Lantana leaf, but we are yet to establish if this is related to feeding, or purely a proximity-related coincidence...

Since we realised that Yellow Bells is categorised as invasive, we did a bit of research...

We came across this interesting fact sheet compiled by Lin Besaans for the Agricultural Research Council, "Mada Polluta, A Lady Beetle Released for Biocontrol of Yellow Bells": https://www.arc.agric.za/arc-ppri/Fact%20Sheets%20Library/Mada%20polluta%20on%20tecoma.pdf.

"The lady beetle Mada polluta Mulsant 1850 (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae) was collected on yellow bells (Tecoma stans) in 2007 in Mexico, where the plant is native, and imported into quarantine in South Africa for screening as a potential biocontrol agent. Following several years of testing, the lady beetle was found to be host specific on yellow bells. Permission was obtained for its release, and the first insects were released at various sites in KwaZulu-Natal, Mpumalanga, Gauteng, and North West in the summer of 2013/2014. Releases are on-going, and the distribution map will be updated once establishment has been determined.

Adult beetles are yellow and black, and are about 5 mm long and 4.34 mm wide. Larvae are yellow, with long, branched spines on the dorsal and lateral surfaces. From first instar to fourth instar, larval body length ranges between 2.51 mm and 5.3 mm. Pupae are yellow and brown, and are covered by the old hard, spiny skin of the larva.

Adult females lay clusters of 3-59 eggs on the underside of leaves. The larvae hatch within 7-10 days and feed on the leaves immediately. Larvae go through 4 larval instars (growth stages) before pupating, and emerge as adults within about 36 days. Adults live for up to 4 months, and females reproduce several times during that period.

Both adults and larvae feed on the leaves and, to a lesser extent, on the stems of yellow bells. They consume the leaf area in narrow, short band sets from left to right, then start again below the first set, but without ever consuming the thin line of leaf area that separates the two adjacent sets. In this manner, they skeletonise the leaf.

The lady beetle is expected to contribute significantly to the biological control of yellow bells in South Africa, owing to several factors. Firstly, both adults and larvae are extremely damaging to the plant. Laboratory studies demonstrated that the insects decrease leaf density significantly, stunting the plant’s growth and reducing its competitive ability. Secondly, adult females reproduce rapidly, thus, beetle populations and their associated damage should increase in the field accordingly. Thirdly, this group of beetles (coccinellids) protect themselves chemically from predators and parasitoids, which enhances their chance of survival and, ultimately, their effect on the target weed. Biological control is the only sustainable solution for yellow bells infestations, and it is hoped that the lady beetle will reduce these plants throughout the country, thereby encouraging the indigenous vegetation to recover."

There's another, more recent article by Marleni Arnoldi in Creamer Media's Engineering News, 19 November 2024: "ARC to release invasive-plant controlling beetles in Umkhomazi": https://m.engineeringnews.co.za/article/arc-to-release-invasive-plant-controlling-beetles-in-umkhomazi-2024-11-19, in which it is reported that:

 "The Agricultural Research Council’s (ARC’s) plant health and protection unit will, on November 25, release a leaf-feeding lady beetle called Mada Polluta in Umkhomazi, KwaZulu-Natal, to act as a biological control agent against invasive yellow bells...The release of the beetle, which is a collaboration project between the Department of Forestry, Fisheries and the Environment, the eThekwini municipality and Ezemvelo KwaZulu-Natal Wildlife, was approved for release in 2013, and efforts are now focused on mass rearing and releasing the beetle to help control yellow bell invasions.

In particular, the release of the beetle in Umkhomazi aims to limit the growth and spread of yellow bells in the region. More releases will occur at selected sites across the province that provide suitable habitat for the beetle."

It would appear the preliminary suggestion to introduce this beetle was based on research conducted in this paper by Lulama Gracious Madire, Biocontrol Science and Technology Volume 23 (2013) - Issue 8: "Biology and host range of Mada polluta, a potential biological control agent of Tecoma stans in South Africa": https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09583157.2013.809404.

According to another article by the same author, Lulama Gracious Madire, in Plant Protection News (October 2016 - March 2017) Issue No 109, "Lady beetle (Mada polluta) fully established on yellow bells (Tecoma stans) on the South Coast of KwaZulu-Natal": https://invasives.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/PPRI-News-109.pdf

"Since the release of this beetle, a number of factors have delayed its establishment, including the destruction of most of the release sites through deliberate felling and burning by landowners after initial establishment. Although the beetles recovered at a few felled sites,
none of the beetles were recovered on burned sites. The destruction of the release sites has not only delayed establishment of the beetle, but has also delayed the commencement of its post-release evaluation."

Well it would appear that this beetle has certainly made its way all the way to Gulu! We've since been finding them on Yellow Bells plants all over the place! 😄

From iNat we see Mada sp. Lady Beetles are Plant-Eating Lady Beetles: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/640755-Mada and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?preferred_place_id=6986&taxon_id=640755&view=species, but there 
are no observations as yet of Mada polluta on iNat despite the name apparently being listed: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/673993-Mada-polluta and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=673993&view=species. 

Update: Thanks to Tony Rebelo Mada polluta is now listed on iNat as the Yellow Bells Ladybeetle. Thanks Tony! 🙂 Thanks also to Jaroslav Větrovec* for confirming the ID 🙂

*Jaroslav Větrovec is "a Coccinellidae specialist" 

We managed to contact Lulu to send her regards from the local beetles and she kindly added that: "Indeed, Mada polluta is well established around East London. I visited East London in March, and it is causing significant damage to the Tecoma stans population. This species is specific to yellow bells; it may be found resting on the leaves of other plants when they are defoliated, but it does not feed on or develop on other plants. It is well established at South coast, KZN and Mpumalanga provinces as well." Thanks for that Lulu! 🙂

Reading up a bit further about Yellow Bells or Tecoma Stans: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/48363-Tecoma-stans and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/48363-Tecoma-stans/browse_photos, we found the following:

"Tecoma stans is a species of flowering perennial shrub in the trumpet vine family, Bignoniaceae, that is native to the Americas. Common names include yellow trumpetbush, yellow bells, yellow elder, ginger Thomas. Tecoma stans is the official flower of the United States Virgin Islands and the floral emblem of The Bahamas.

Tecoma stans is a semi-evergreen shrub or small tree, growing up to 10 m tall. It features opposite odd-pinnate green leaves, with 3 to 13 serrate, 8- to 10-cm-long leaflets. The leaflets, glabrous on both sides, have a lanceolate blade 2–10 cm long and 1–4 cm wide, with a long acuminate apex and a wedge-shaped base.

The large, showy, golden yellow, trumpet-shaped flowers are in clusters at the ends of branches. The corolla of the flower is bell- to funnel-shaped, five-lobed (weakly two-lipped), often reddish-veined in the throat and is 3.5 to 8.5 cm long. Flowering takes place from spring to fall, but more profusely from spring to summer.

The fruits, narrow capsules, arise from two carpels and are up to 25 cm long. A fruit contains many yellow seeds with membranopus wings; when the fruit opens upon ripening, these seed are spread by the wind (anemochory). The flowers attract bees, butterflies, and hummingbirds. Apart from sexually by seed, Tecoma stans can also be reproduced asexually by stem cuttings. 

Tecoma stans is native to the Americas. It extends from the southern United States through Mexico, Central America, and the Antilles to northern Venezuela, and through the Andes mountain range to northern Argentina. It was introduced in southern Africa, India, and Hawaii. It is evergreen in moist and warmer regions, but is deciduous in more temperate regions that have a pronounced dry season.

Yellow trumpetbush is a ruderal species, readily colonizing disturbed, rocky, sandy, and cleared land and occasionally becoming an invasive weed. It thrives in a wide variety of ecosystems, from high altitude temperate forests and tropical deciduous and evergreen forests, to xerophilous scrub and the intertropical littoral. It quickly colonizes disturbed, rocky, sandy, and cleared fields. The species prefers dry and sunny regions of the coast. 

Tecoma stans is drought-tolerant and grows well in warm climates. It is cultivated as an ornamental. They are grown in many parts of the world for their beautiful flowering, to adorn streets and gardens. It can be easily propagated by stem cuttings.

The wood of Tecoma stans is used in rustic architecture like bahareque, for the construction of furniture and canoes, or as firewood or charcoal. It is a medicinal plant used against diabetes and against diseases of the digestive system, among other uses. The plant is desirable fodder when it grows in fields grazed by livestock.

It is a very potent anti-venom against cobra venom, used by Pakistani old medicine. It is proved to be better than antiserum, the paste of this plant's leaves are applied topically on the cobra bite. Its bio-chemicals bind with the cobra venom enzymes thus effectively inhibiting the venom.

Tecoma stans is unique in that although it is nontoxic itself, the honey from its flowers is poisonous nonetheless.

Tecoma stans has invasive potential and occasionally becomes a weed. The species is considered invasive in Africa (especially South Africa), South America, Asia, Australia and the Pacific Islands. It now presents a significant danger for biodiversity. It competes with local species and can form thick, almost monospecific thickets."

A solo visit. I started late (1150) because I could not motivate myself to get out of bed. The weather at my arrival was sunny and 91 degrees ("feels like" 100), with a light breeze. I surveyed Scrub Island Road for the first time this year, and I found an old logging tram that headed west from the end of the road. I followed the tram until it ended; it was a nice shady walk, and provided me with my first Appalachian Brown of Chassahowitzka. (The tram also furnished my first EVER photograph of a Barred Owl in Hernando County!!! Talk about being long overdue)! There were also many Needle Palms along the tram. I stopped at the Dukes' Skippper spot along 3 Bridge Road (finding little) before I headed to my final spot near the start of North Road. I once again encountered an agitated female "Southestern" American Kestrel, so there must be a nest in the kestrel box. I left at 1501, when the weather was sunny, 94 degrees ("feels like" 104), and breezy.

These are my cell-phone photographs (161 records), all time-stamped and geolocated.

Pawpaw Webworm Moth: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/289667264

description: Along social trail, downstream from Lilly Bridge.

Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1BpEUpHHWP

Fascinating goings on at our aphid-covered rose bush. 

There is so much going on here! We were amazed to read how complex the life cycle of an aphid is: https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aphid. Apparently aphid populations can sometimes even be entirely female and each one can give birth to live young who are themselves born pregnant! Apparently it's called "telescoping of generations". How's that for a party trick? 😮

The winged ones are apparently produced under unfavourable or stressful conditions so that they can fly off to a new food source.

From René Laing's posting: https://www.facebook.com/groups/Butterfliesandbugs/permalink/7019964178101022/, and with some help from Warren Keith Dick, the caterpillar-like visitor to the left in the 3rd piccy is possibly an aphid-munching hoverfly larva.

⚠️🚧🚫
Edit1: According to Mark G Wright, these are most likely Green Peach-Aphids, Greenflies or Peach-Potato Aphids - Myzus persicae: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/243745-Myzus-persicae and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/243745-Myzus-persicae/browse_photos and, although they are both green, these are *not* Potato Aphids - Macrosiphum eiphorbiae: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/53859-Macrosiphum-euphorbiae and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/53859-Macrosiphum-euphorbiae/browse_photos, since Green Peach-Aphids are "a highly variable species". Thanks for lending a trained eye there Mark! Appearances can certainly be deceptive with these suckers! 😊 
⚠️🚧🚫

Edit2: Well apparently these little things are even more deceptive than one would imagine - thanks to Annari-du-plessis for flagging the ID and Natalie Hernandez* for clarifying that apparently "Myzus persicae doesn't have black siphunculi (the tailpipes): https://influentialpoints.com/Gallery/Myzus_persicae_Peach-potato_aphid.htm
https://influentialpoints.com/Gallery/Macrosiphum_rosae_Rose_aphid.htm."

*Natalie has a B.S. and M.Sc. in Entomology from the University of Wisconsin - Madison (USA) and her graduate research focused on alate aphids.

So it looks as if these little things are in fact Common Rose Aphids, Macrosiphum rosae: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/53633-Macrosiphum-rosae and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/53633-Macrosiphum-rosae/browse_photos.

"Macrosiphum rosae, the rose aphid, is a species of sap-sucking aphids in the subfamily Aphidinae. They have a world-wide distribution and infest rosebushes as the main host in spring and early summer, congregating on the tips of shoots and around new buds. Later in the summer, winged forms move to other rose bushes, or to a limited number of secondary hosts, before returning to rosebushes to lay eggs in the autumn.

Wingless adults have a spindle-shaped body and are between 1.7 and 3.6 mm long, slender, varying in colour from green to pink and reddish-brown. The antennae and legs are relatively long, and the cauda (tail-like protrusion) is pale. The siphunculi (pair of small backward-pointing tubes on the abdomen) are long, tapered and black, which distinguishes this aphid from Metopolophium dirhodum, the rose-grain aphid, which has pale siphunculi. Winged individuals are between 2.2 and 3.4 mm in length, varying from green to pinkish-brown, and having distinctive black lateral markings.

This aphid mainly overwinters as eggs on roses, but in mild winters, some adults may survive until spring. The eggs hatch in spring into wingless females which reproduce parthenogenetically, and large colonies can quickly develop, being mainly found on the tips of shoots and around flower buds. The heaviest population densities are in June and July in the northern hemisphere, just when the bushes are flowering, and thereafter the populations decline. This is because at this time of year, some winged females develop, which migrate to other rose bushes or to certain secondary hosts such as holly, teasel, valerian, Knautia and scabious. With the onset of autumn, winged males are also produced, the insects return to roses and the eggs are laid.

Rose aphids damage the aesthetic appearance of rosebushes by contorting the flowers and foliage, and by the sticky honeydew they produce, which often provides a surface on which sooty moulds develop."

Update: At around the same time as this observation, we saw a Red Flower Assassin Bug hunting these aphids on the roses here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/288154962.

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1AhKZuJwNw

From strange, to stranger...💛🧡💚🤎❣😄

A little while ago we discovered a really bizarre-looking larva on our Lemon tree: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/290835898. Much to our surprise it was actually eating the Lemon 🍋 leaves! 

Joy duToit le Roux and Steve Woodhall told us that it's apparently the larva of a Common Swallowtail: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=47225&view=species, maybe even that of a Greenband Swallowtail or Southern Narrow-Banded Malachite, Papilio nireus ssp. lyaeus: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/347039-Papilio-nireus-lyaeus. Thanks Annari du Plessis, Colin Ralston and Andrew Morton for also confirming the ID for us 🙂

We thought that was quite amazing and decided to try to rear it, together with another one we also found nearby, to see what might emerge.

The fascinating caterpillar transformation process, itself, has already been totally worth it!

Here is one of the larvae. 

It looks a bit like a piece of excrement - orange, green black and white, decorated with odd little spines. 

When you get close to the larva, a bright red set of snail-like "horns" suddenly pops out! We sure didn't see *that* one coming! 😄

If the larva stills feels threatened then it raises its upper body into the air and tucks its head under, looking, for all the world, *just* like a fresh deposit! 😄

Quite amazing...

Update: We later got to see 😃 how these larvae developed into glorious velvety-green caterpillars here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/290847738.

Some time later we got to see the first emergent butterfly, a male here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/290854451.

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/191zCmDv7e

These tiny things have the cutest little feet! 😄

We found this gorgeous fluffy Lady Beetle munching on a leaf - the plant looks  as if it's possibly some type of Solanum.

The beetle looks quite similar to either a Solanophila cf. infirma: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/690050-Solanophila-infirma, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/690050-Solanophila-infirma/browse_photos 

⚠️🚧🚫
or a Chnootriba cf. natalensis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1535496-Chnootriba-natalensis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1535496-Chnootriba-natalensis/browse_photos.
⚠️🚧🚫

Edit1: According to Johan Bogaert this lovely beetle is more likely to be a Solanophila infirma because Chnootriba natalensis has 1 spot more on the before last row and Chnootriba tricolorata has 1 spot more in the first row. Well spotted Johan! We really appreciate your eye for detail! 🔍👁 😃 Thank you also to Colin Ralston for joining us in this journey of discovery!

Edit2: According to Michael Griffiths the plant is a Drunken Berry, Solanum africanum: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/526198-Solanum-africanum and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/526198-Solanum-africanum/browse_photos. Thanks Michael! 🙂

"Solanum africanum is a species of plant in the nightshade family. It is found in South Africa. This plant typically occurs near the coast up to an altitude of 200m.

Solanum africanum is a perennial, herbaceous shrub or climber growing up to 3 meters tall. The flowers are white to purple with a yellow centre, borne in pendulous clusters at the branch tips. The leaves are simple in shape, green, ovate to elliptic or lanceolate with an acute apex, and the margin is often entire, but occasionally lobed. While growing flat on the ground without a support to keep it upright, the plant sends out branches in all directions, which may be seen. It's possible that this growth behavior is why the plant is occasionally called the drunken rope or berry. The fruit is a round berry, black when ripe, 15mm in diameter.

Solanum africanum is a member of the family Solanaceae. This family includes nightshade, tomato, potato and chillies.

This species is frequently found near coastal dunes in the bush. It occurs from Cape Peninsula to KwaZulu-Natal. It flowers at any time of the year."

or a Chnootriba cf. natalensis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1535496-Chnootriba-natalensis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1535496-Chnootriba-natalensis/browse_photos.
⚠️🚧🚫

Edit1: According to Johan Bogaert this lovely beetle is more likely to be a Solanophila infirma because Chnootriba natalensis has 1 spot more on the before last row and Chnootriba tricolorata has 1 spot more in the first row. Well spotted Johan! We really appreciate your eye for detail! 🔍👁 😃 Thank you also to Colin Ralston for joining us in this journey of discovery!

Edit2: According to Michael Griffiths the plant is a Drunken Berry, Solanum africanum: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/526198-Solanum-africanum and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/526198-Solanum-africanum/browse_photos. Thanks Michael! 🙂 Thanks also plantperson7654 for confirming the ID for us - we appreciate it very much 🙂

"Solanum africanum is a species of plant in the nightshade family. It is found in South Africa. This plant typically occurs near the coast up to an altitude of 200m.

Solanum africanum is a perennial, herbaceous shrub or climber growing up to 3 meters tall. The flowers are white to purple with a yellow centre, borne in pendulous clusters at the branch tips. The leaves are simple in shape, green, ovate to elliptic or lanceolate with an acute apex, and the margin is often entire, but occasionally lobed. While growing flat on the ground without a support to keep it upright, the plant sends out branches in all directions, which may be seen. It's possible that this growth behavior is why the plant is occasionally called the drunken rope or berry. The fruit is a round berry, black when ripe, 15mm in diameter.

Solanum africanum is a member of the family Solanaceae. This family includes nightshade, tomato, potato and chillies.

This species is frequently found near coastal dunes in the bush. It occurs from Cape Peninsula to KwaZulu-Natal. It flowers at any time of the year."

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1QuqLCkuvK

This plant observation is a passive partner observation to the seed-eating Riptortus sp. Bug observation here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/294887174

The hairy seeds stick to absolutely everything - we were completely covered in them after filming, and spent ages picking them off our clothing. Since we involuntarily ended up with so many, we decided to open one up to see what the inner yumminess looks like. It actually looks quite soft and young pea-like in texture...and yes...we had a tiny nibble to see what it tastes like! 😄 It does actually taste a bit sweet, like a tiny fresh pea! Who would have guessed...apparently the bugs did! 😁

Alan Manson suggested an ID for this plant as possibly being a Ticktrefoil, Desmodium sp. Thanks Alan, that's very helpful! 🙂

Looking further we see that it may even be a Creeping Beggarweed, Desmodium incanum: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/116694-Desmodium-incanum and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/116694-Desmodium-incanum/browse_photos. Thanks for confirming the ID for us crispus_k 🙂

"Desmodium incanum, also known as creeping beggarweed, Spanish clover, Spanish tick-trefoil or hitchhikers is a perennial plant native to Central and South America. In Hawaii it is known as kaʻimi or kaimi clover from the Hawaiian for 'seeker'. Initially introduced as forage crop around the world, it has spread to many places although it is no longer an important fodder crop. It is considered a weed both within and outside its native range. It has spread through Florida and across the southern USA into southern Texas and across many Pacific islands, including Hawaii.

The plant has branched runners for reproduction. Its leaves are elliptic in shape and are hairy, and its flowers are pink to rose in color. Very frustrating in agriculture are its seedpods, which when ripe easily break off from the plant. They are also covered in sticky hairs (trichomes) that stick to any rough surface such as skin and hairs of animals and clothing thus aiding spreading. D. incanum is valuable for its ability to fix Nitrogen and thus increase soil fertility, thus it is commonly used as an intercrop...

In West Africa, a blue dye is obtained from Desmodium incanum."

According to Wikipedia, "Desmodium" is derived from the Greek word desmos which means "bond, fetter, or chain," referring to the connected segments of the fruit (legume) giving it a chain-like appearance (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desmodium_tweedyi) and according the Consortium of Midwest Herbaria "incanum" means greyish or hoary (https://midwestherbaria.org/portal/taxa/index.php?taxon=3677&clid=97109).

Thanks for confirming the ID for us Colin Ralston and Dawid Jacobs 🙂

🌍 The bee is separately posted here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/298897190.

It's possibly an an African Honeybee or East African lowland honey bee, Apis mellifera ssp. scutellata: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/121322-Apis-mellifera-scutellata, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/121322-Apis-mellifera-scutellata/browse_photos.

🌍 The flies are separately posted here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/298897841.

They're possibly Jackal Flies or Freeloader Flies classified in the Milichiidae family: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/329891-Milichiidae and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&preferred_place_id=6986&taxon_id=329891&view=species. Thanks for confirming this ID Johan Pretorius 🙂

"Milichiidae are a family of flies. Most species are very small and dark. Details of their biology have not yet been properly studied, but they are best known as kleptoparasites of predatory invertebrates, and accordingly are commonly known as freeloader flies or jackal flies. However, because of the conditions under which many species breed out, they also are known as filth flies."

description:
A solo visit after four days of frequent all-day rain; I simply had to get out somewhere, 
and I had not visited Perry Oldenburg in at least two months. I walked a unique path today: the west fenceline to the south fenceline, then northeast under the powerline to the east-west trail that continues east from Yes Dear Lane, then south along the east fenceline, cross country (through recent burns) to the nature trail, clockwise, under the powerline to continue along the southern nature trail to the lake, then along its eastern side to the northern nature trail back to Little Red. The weather at the start (1112) was overcast, 88 degrees ("feels like" 100, with probably 95% humidity), with a light breeze. The weather was the same when I left at 1421. Several observations: (1) There were 20 or more cocoons on the western barbed-wire fenceline; iNat's AI identified them as Southern Flannel Moths (Megalopyge opercularis), which makes sense. (2) Several dozen butterflies (swallowtails including many Zebra Swallowtails, Zebra Longwing, Gulf Fritillary, Southern Dogface, and duskywings) were nectaring abundantly on Florida Pusley (Richardia scabra) at the very southwestern corner of the preserve; I was not aware it was such a butterfly plant. (3) It was a great mushroom/fungus day, with hundreds of individuals of many species (too bad most will never be RGed). (4) Clusterspike False Indigo (Amorpha herbacea) is just starting to bloom. (5) Manyflower Beardtongue (Penstemon multiflorus) is blooming abundantly under the powerline. (6) The trail along the powerline is growing up with grasses and forbs; I found no tiger beetles here (although I found two elsewhere). (7) Florida False Sunflower (Phoebanthus grandiflorus) was blooming over much of the preserve, especially along the southern nature trail west of the powerline. (8) About every third Florida False Sunflower bloom had an Orange Blister Beetle (Nemognatha piazata) on it. (9) Sand Post Oak (Quercus margaretiae) has very attractive leaves when young; I photographed several in a recently-burned area. (10) The lake is finally receding after being formed in October 2024 following the passage of one or two hurricanes. Dozens of flooded Slash Pine skeletons dot the former boundary. (11) I probably got some lifer plants; I can't think of any insect that might be a lifer, and I saw very few spiders or vertebrates (although three Green Anoles was nice).

These are my cell-phone photographs (representing 226 records), all time-stamped and geolocated.
place_guess: Florida, Hernando, Perry Oldenburg Wildlife and Environmental Area

description:
This bald eagle slipped in right after the other and thus avoided most of the gull swarm, since they were still regrouping after the first, just a moment earlier. Both took murres. Since the two flew off together to the same area, it seems likely they're mates.

Twelve minutes later, an eagle flew in again, and got another murre. After staring at the photos for a long time, I believe it was this eagle, again, due to the pattern of feather breakage in the wings. It didn't get to avoid the gulls this time, and took another murre, as seen in the fifth photo.

Prey: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/296198155

Other eagle, possible mate: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/296198161

description:
A lovely bush of violet flowers 💜

Some time ago we came across this gorgeous plant with an explosion of stunning lilac-coloured flowers. We were instantly besotted and hoped we would somehow still discover some other small critters on the plant which we subsequently did here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/297523521 💜😄

Iain Darbyshire* kindly identified the plant as a Blue Bushviolet, Barleria obtusa: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/427994-Barleria-obtusa, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/427994-Barleria-obtusa/browse_photos and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/296822088.

"Barleria obtusa, the bush violet, is a species of flowering plant in the family Acanthaceae. It occurs naturally along forest margins in the summer rainfall region of South Africa (Free State, KwaZulu-Natal, and the Northern Provinces) and in Mozambique. It is widely cultivated as a decorative garden shrub.

In tropical Africa, the leaves are cooked as a vegetable, and the plant is used medicinally."

*Dr. Iain Darbyshire is "A research botanist focusing on the plant diversity of Africa and Madagascar, with a specialist interest in Acanthaceae. Also really interested in an amateur way in the UK flora."

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1B3gdZfoYu

What is this caterpillar doing? 🤔

Eating? Or possibly preparing to make a pupal housing? Maybe something like the one we found on top of a similar thistle-like plant here?: https://www.facebook.com/groups/Butterfliesandbugs/posts/what-caterpillar-makes-its-home-like-this-and-what-will-it-becomepeering-through/8405900492840710/

It's about 11mm long...

Edit: According to Suncana Bradley "it's probably an early instar Painted Lady, Vanessa cardui": https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/48548-Vanessa-cardui and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/48548-Vanessa-cardui/browse_photos. Thanks Suncana! 🧡 Thanks also Steve Woodhall for confirming the caterpillar ID for us 🙂

Mark G Wright also commented that it looks as if the caterpillar is "mowing the trichomes". Thanks Mark 🙂 

We scurried off to find out what trichomes are...Apparently "Trichomes (/ˈtraɪkoʊmz, ˈtrɪkoʊmz/; from Ancient Greek τρίχωμα (tríkhōma) 'hair') are fine outgrowths or appendages on plants, algae, lichens, and certain protists. They are of diverse structure and function. Examples are hairs, glandular hairs, scales, and papillae. A covering of any kind of hair on a plant is an indumentum, and the surface bearing them is said to be pubescent." (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trichome) Fascinating! 

The thistle is most likely a Berkheya bipinnatifida ssp. bipinnatifida: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/597959-Berkheya-bipinnatifida-bipinnatifida and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/597959-Berkheya-bipinnatifida-bipinnatifida/browse_photos.

Interestingly we later found a Belonogaster wasp also mowing the trichomes on a pubescent Guava leaf in order to make nesting material here: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/12HEFn63MgH

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/16gNF5BvMn

©️ This is a duplicate of the Millipede post here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/298326719.

Over the last while we keep finding these dinky little millipedes 😃

We found one about 35mm long here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/298218967 and another one only about 11mm long here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/298223001.

When we first saw the "bigger" one it looked as if it may possibly be eating the trichomes on the leaves of a thistle.

This little one is a "whopping" 14mm long and once again it looks as if it may be eating trichomes, only this time they are Lantana trichomes! These millipedes don't seem to mind too much where they're mowing 😄

Edit: According to Clare Archer*, this particular Lantana is most likely to be a Lantana, Lantana camara: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/50333-Lantana-camara and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/50333-Lantana-camara/browse_photos. Thanks so much Clare, that's really interesting! The flowers on iNat most definitely look like the local pink and yellow ones we have here! 🙂

*Clare is a "Former plant scientist and passionate naturalist. Published research primarily on sedges of southern Africa. Curated and identified - mainly for southern Africa - all monocot families (except grasses) and ferns at various times." 

"Lantana camara (common lantana) or “Florida Flower” as is sometimes called, is a species of flowering plant in the verbena family (Verbenaceae), native to the American tropics. It is a very adaptable species, which can inhabit a wide variety of ecosystems; once it has been introduced into a habitat it spreads rapidly; between 45ºN and 45ºS and less than 1,400 metres in altitude.

It has spread from its native range to around 50 countries, where it has become an invasive species. It first spread out of the Americas when it was brought to Europe by Dutch explorers and cultivated widely, soon spreading further into Asia and Oceania where it has established itself as a notorious weed, and in Goa Former Estado da Índia Portuguesa it was introduced by the Portuguese.

L. camara can outcompete native species, leading to a reduction in biodiversity. It can also cause problems if it invades agricultural areas as a result of its toxicity to livestock, as well as its ability to form dense thickets which, if left unchecked, can greatly reduce the productivity of farmland by suppressing the pastures (grasses) essential for livestock production and also suppresses crops in cultivated farmlands.

Lantana camara is a perennial, erect sprawling or scandent, shrub which typically grows to around 2 metres tall and form dense thickets in a variety of environments. Under the right conditions, it can scramble up into trees and can grow to 6 m tall.

The leaves are broadly ovate, opposite, and simple and have a strong odour when crushed.

L. camara has small tubular-shaped flowers, which each have four petals and are arranged in clusters in terminal areas stems. Flowers come in many different colours, including red, yellow, white, pink and orange, which differ depending on location in inflorescences, age, and maturity. The flower has a tutti frutti smell with a peppery undertone. After pollination occurs, the colour of the flowers changes (typically from yellow to orangish, pinkish, or reddish); this is believed to be a signal to pollinators that the pre-change colour contains a reward as well as being sexually viable, thus increasing pollination efficiency. In frost-free climates the plant can bloom all year round, especially when the soil is moist.

There are five major flower colour varieties in Australia:

Pink – Bud: pink; Middle ring: yellow opening with pale yellow petals; Outer ring: orange opening with pale or dark pink petals
White – Bud: cream coloured; Middle ring: yellow opening with light yellow petals; Outer ring: orange or yellow opening with lilac petals
Pink-edged Red – Bud: pink to reddish pink; Middle ring: orange opening with light yellow to orange petals; Outer ring: orange opening having two pink to red petals
Red – Bud: blood red; Middle ring: yellow opening with yellow petals; Outer ring: red throat having red petals
Orange – Bud: orange; Middle ring: yellow to orange opening, yellow petals; Outer ring: orange opening with orange petals

The fruit is a berry-like drupe which turns from green to dark purple when mature. Green unripe fruits are inedible to humans and animals alike. Because of dense patches of hard spikes on their rind, ingestion of them can result in serious damage to the digestive tract. Both seed and vegetative reproduction occur. Up to 12,000 fruits can be produced by each plant.

Due to extensive selective breeding throughout the 17th and 18th centuries for use as an ornamental plant, there are now many different cultivars.

Other common names include Cariaquillo (Boriken, Puerto Rico), Visepo (Zambia),Spanish flag, big-sage (Malaysia), Putush (West Bengal), Kongini (Kerala), Ghaneri घाणेरी (Maharashtra), wild-sage, red-sage, white-sage (Caribbean), korsu wiri or korsoe wiwiri (Suriname), mũkigĩ (Kenya), tickberry (South Africa), Kashi Kothan (Maldives), West Indian lantana, umbelanterna, and Gu Phool in Assam, and Thirei in Manipur, and Banfada in Nepal.

The name Lantana derives from the Latin name of the wayfaring tree Viburnum lantana, the flowers of which closely resemble Lantana.

Camara is derived from an indigenous Brazilian name for this, and several other plants.

The native range of Lantana camara is Central and South America; however, it has become naturalised in around 60 tropical and sub-tropical countries worldwide. It is found frequently in east and southern Africa, where it occurs at altitudes below 2,000 m, and often invades previously disturbed areas such as logged forests and areas cleared for agriculture. L. camara has also spread across the areas of Africa, Southern Europe, such as Spain and Portugal, and also the Middle East, India, tropical Asia, Australia, New Zealand, and the US, as well as many Atlantic, Pacific and Indian Ocean islands. It has become a significant weed in Sri Lanka after escaping from the Royal Botanical Gardens in 1926. Lantanas were brought to Australia as an ornamental garden plant in 1841, which spread and escaped domestic cultivation and became established in the wild within 20 years. They were brought to India by the British around 200 years ago, which then spread and became invasive there as well. A national-level monitoring in 2023 found that L. camara has invaded around 50% of the natural areas in India.

It was introduced into the Philippines from Hawaii as part of an exchange program between the United States and the Philippines; however, it managed to escape and has become naturalized in the islands. It has also been introduced to the whole southern US, from California to North Carolina, and is considered hardy in US Department of Agriculture zones 10 and 11.

The range of L. camara is still increasing, shown by the fact that it has invaded many islands on which it was not present in 1974, including the Galapagos Islands, Saipan and the Solomon Islands. There is also evidence that L. camara is still increasing its range in areas where it has been established for many years, such as East Africa, Australia and New Zealand. The ability of L. camara to rapidly colonise areas of land which have been disturbed has allowed it to proliferate in countries where activities such as logging, clearance for agriculture and forest fires are common. In contrast, in countries with large areas of intact primary forest, the distribution of L. camara has been limited.

Birds and other animals eat the seeds, helping spread them over large distances.

The species is found in a variety of environments, including:

Agricultural areas
Forest margins and gaps
Riparian zones
Grasslands
Secondary forest, and
Beach fronts.

L. camara is rarely found in natural or semi-natural areas of forest, as it is unable to compete with taller trees due to its lack of tolerance for shade. Instead it grows at the forest edge. L. camara can survive in a wide range of climatic conditions, including drought, different soil types, heat, humidity and salt. It is also relatively fire tolerant and can quickly establish itself in recently burnt areas of forest.

Extension Gardener website states that ingestion of the flowers, fruits, and leaves can cause vomiting, diarrhea, difficulty breathing, and liver failure, while the leaves can cause contact dermatitis. A field guide by the US Department of the Army says the plant can even be fatal. Contrarily, some studies have claimed that the species poses no risk to humans when eaten, and is in fact edible when ripe.

Lantana camara stalks have been used in the construction of furniture, such as chairs and tables; however, the main uses have historically been medicinal and ornamental.

Studies conducted in India have found that Lantana leaves can display antimicrobial, fungicidal and insecticidal properties. L. camara has also been used in traditional herbal medicines for treating a variety of ailments, including cancer, skin itches, leprosy, chicken pox, measles, asthma and ulcers.

L. camara extract has shown to reduce gastric ulcer development in rats.

Lantana camara has been grown specifically for use as an ornamental plant since Dutch explorers first brought it to Europe from the New World. Its ability to last for a relatively long time without water, and the fact that it does not have many pests or diseases which affect it, have contributed to it becoming a common ornamental plant. L. camara also attracts butterflies and birds and is frequently used in butterfly gardens. As an ornamental, L. camara is often cultivated indoors, or in a conservatory, in cool climates, but can also thrive in a garden with sufficient shelter.

Many butterfly species feed on the nectar of L. camara. Papilio homerus, the largest butterfly in the western hemisphere, is known to feed on the nectar of the flowers as an opportunistic flower feeder. A jumping spider, Evarcha culicivora, has an association with L. camara. They consume the nectar for food and preferentially use these plants as a location for courtship."

Wow! What a story! 😅 We're glad to see this little millipede doing its tiny biocontrol thing! In this case it would appear that every tiny contribution is helpful! 😄🥰🤗

Edit2: Apparently, according to James K Douch*, this millie is also a member of the Ring Millipedes (Juliformia Superorder): https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/372724-Juliformia and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/372724-Juliformia/browse_photos. Thanks so much James! 🙂

*James K Douch is "a Ph.D. cand. (Macquarie Univ.). Phylogenetics & taxonomy of Onychophora."

"Juliformia is a taxonomic superorder of millipedes containing three living orders: Julida, Spirobolida, and Spirostreptida, and the extinct group Xyloiuloidea known only from fossils.

The species possess long cylindrical bodies with sclerites (skeletal plates consisting of ventral sternites, lateral pleurites, and dorsal tergites) fused into complete rings. Juliform millipedes possess defensive repugnatorial glands on all body segments except the last few, and are the only known millipedes to produce quinones in their defensive secretions. Juliform males have two pairs of gonopods consisting of the modified 8th and 9th pair of legs: in Julida and Spirobolida the posterior gonopods (9th leg pair) are primarily involved in sperm-transferring, while in Spirostreptida it is the anterior gonopods (8th leg pair). Juliformians also lack Tömösváry organs and have a large collum (first body segment) which overhangs the rear of the head."

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1ZsZzbeiSW

What a beauty! 🖤🤍❣😃

We found these gorgeous Assassins, with their black and white polka-dots and red-striped edges, on one of our Gooseberry bushes. 

It looks as if one of them is eating what may possibly be a larva or "slug" of a Tobacco Slug Beetle: Lema cf. bilineata: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/672328-Lema-bilineata, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/672328-Lema-bilineata/browse_photos and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/298736487.

These are Assassin Bugs (Reduviidae family): https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=48959&view=species and possibly Dark Flower Assassins, Rhynocoris tristis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/632509-Rhynocoris-tristis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/632509-Rhynocoris-tristis/browse_photos. Thanks Dawid Jacobs and Colin Ralston for confirming the ID 🙂

"Rhynocoris tristis is a species of assassin bug family (Reduviidae), in the subfamily Harpactorinae. R. tristis is a polyphagous predator found in sub-Saharan Africa.

R. tristis is associated with Stylosanthes guinaensis, and this association is thought to be due to the prey species attracted by flowers of S. guinaensis [https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/281731-Stylosanthes-guianensis]. R. tristis is unusual in the insect world in that males provide paternal care by guarding egg masses from parasitic wasps and insect predators. Males will also cannibalize some of the eggs that they guard. R. tristis prefers to lay its eggs on the stems of plants, in contrast to most members of the harpactorinae, which prefer to lay them on the undersides of leaves."

Update: About ten days later we found a nymph of one of these types of Bugs here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/299487110.

Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1CKJgQGPJ1

Interesting...🤔

These bugs are each about 8mm long.

Nearly two months ago we first discovered some similar bugs in the bush: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/299146233.

Apparently these are the nymphs of one of the Jewel Bugs or Shield-Backed Bugs (Scutelleriidae family): https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/49525-Scutelleridae and possibly that of a Calidea sp.: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/126979-Calidea and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=126979&view=species.

It looks as if these nymphs are similar to those recorded as belonging to Calidea cf. humeralis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1405849-Calidea-humeralis, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1405849-Calidea-humeralis/browse_photos and compare with https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/37387514.

We've been observing how these types of bugs remain clustered together as nymphs for some time now e.g. here where there's a new cluster: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/299154003 and here where the members of an older cluster are starting to lose their orange stripes: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/299155695.

Here we now see them on what is most likely a Common Wildhop, Dalechampia cf. capensis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/583424-Dalechampia-capensis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/583424-Dalechampia-capensis/browse_photos.

"Dalechampia capensis is a species of shrub. It is known by the common names inzula or wild hop. It is native to Botswana, South Africa, Mozambique, Eswatini, Tanzania, and Zambia. The species is eaten by larval Byblia ilithyia and Eurytela dryope [butterflies]."

Update: We later discovered that these bugs are possibly instars of an adult orange and black adult bug (11mm long) here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/299163775. 

The bug is possibly a Hibiscus Shieldbug, Graptocoris cf. aulicus: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/752454-Graptocoris-aulicus and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/752454-Graptocoris-aulicus/browse_photos. Thanks Dawid Jacobs and Colin Ralston for confirming this ID for us 🙂

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1CmtibZYMj

Amaziiiiing! 🧡🤎😃

Some time ago we came across one of these completely bizarre-looking stealth moths on our Lemon tree - it had only just emerged from its pupa: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/299859852.

Today we saw another one in the garden and we even got to film it a little bit. The colours are a bit darker with this one, presumably because it's a bit older, but It's still one of the weirdest moths we've ever seen! 😄 

It looks different in every type of light and from every angle...we just couldn't stop taking piccies and following it around! 😄 *Very* peculiar...

From what we saw, it looks as if the wings under the leathery exterior are indeed orange 🧡

This is most likely a member of the Tortricid family of Leafroller Moths: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=47155&view=species and possibly a Choristoneura sp.

It looks similar to Choristoneura cf. heliaspis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/657370-Choristoneura-heliaspis, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/657370-Choristoneura-heliaspis/browse_photos and https://www.afromoths.net/species/18144. Thanks for confirming the ID for us Garth Aiston and for your assistance and confirmation of the moth ID Scott K Johnsgard 🙂

"Choristoneura heliaspis is a species of moth of the family Tortricidae. It is found in Ethiopia, Nigeria, South Africa and Mozambique."

Over the last while we actually found quite a few more of the rolled leaf edges on our Lemon tree - and we even got to see one of the pupal casings up close - there must definitely be quite a few more of these moths around somewhere! 😀

Update: We later ended up rearing a very similar-looking moth that curled itself into some sweet potato leaves: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/300040262. 

It looked just like the male ♂ Choristoneura cf. heliaspis depicted in Fig. 17 of an article called "Tortricidae (Lepidoptera) from South Africa. 6: Choristoneura HÜBNER and Procrica DIAKONOFF" by Józef Razowski in the Polish Journal of Entomology (77 (3): 245-254, 2008): https://sparrow.up.poznan.pl/pte/ppe/PJE_2008/26_Razowski.pdf. 

The moth in the present post looks very similar to the female ♀ depicted in Fig. 18 of the same document 😃
