description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1AwVV7M8gJ

A Cutie! 😍🐛

We recently brought some Sweet Potato vines in from the garden, only to discover this cute caterpillar.

It has a bronze 🤎 head with a thick white stripe 🤍 and a transparent greenish 💚 body - quite unusual!

We took it inside on 16 June 2025, and it spun a little curly house to shed its tiny skin on 23 June.

Once it was out, it proceeded to munch further on the leaves, all the while spinning temporary leaf-curled houses as it went along - quite an innovative way to hide from hungry predators such as wasps on the lookout for caterpillars!

It finally settled down to pupate on 06 July. 

At that stage the whole construction was about 1cm long.

We waited and watched in wonder - what would emerge? 🤔

Update: About 15 days later a rather surprisingly familiar-looking bronze mothlet emerged! 👀: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/300040262

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/16ERhPiUq5

We're very excited to find another caterpillar - this time on a Common Fig tree, Ficus carica: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/60218-Ficus-carica. Thanks for the ID confirmation Troos van der Merwe 🙂

This one looks more like a cross between a white, woolly bear and a dachshund - or maybe it's a poodlerpillar? 🐩🐛 🤔 

We thought we'd try to rear it to give it a chance before the wasps get it 🙂

Edit: Steve Woodhall and Suncana Bradley helped us out with this one. As Steve pointed out, it looks like a bird dropping which is common to Lepidopteran larvae and since it seems to be eating Fig leaves he suggested that it's possibly the larva of a Racinoa ficicola moth: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/687106-Racinoa-ficicola and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/687106-Racinoa-ficicola/browse_photos. 

On looking this up we found there is indeed one suggested caterpillar on iNat, a slightly older one, that would certainly fit and has similar markings to this one: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/191977559. Our own Suncana was actually the one who suggested the ID on iNat! 😄🥰 Thanks Steve and Suncana - wonderful teamwork unbeknownst to yourselves 🤗

Interestingly, since the caterpillar and moth have a somewhat similar appearance to that of a Silkworm, we wondered whether this caterpillar would also eat Mulberry and/or Lettuce leaves...according to Steve "They might... Figs and Mulberries are in the same plant family (Moraceae)." We'll certainly have to add it to the menu to see what it prefers 🤔🙂

Update: The little caterpillar aka "Nathaniel" has shed its first skin and changed from salty white to peppery brown: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/300927366

Still later it spun a beautiful white cocoon, and eleven days later it emerged as a lovely little male moth: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/300932663

Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/14HURe89orY

The nest-(eggplant)egg has borne fruit! 🍆🐛😲🍆💜😅 😃 

About one and a half months ago we harvested some eggplants/aubergines/brinjals from our garden and discovered that somebody else (with suspiciously round, pink and pulsating tummies...) had gotten in ahead if us! 🐛😲: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/301432695. 

At that stage we thought it likely that they could be typical Aubergine-eating caterpillars, the Eggplant/Aubergine/Brinjal Fruit and Shoot Borer, Leucinodes orbonalis: https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leucinodes_orbonalis, but according to this article they are apparently "not present in Africa".

To be honest we thought the pink culprits were actually quite cute ☺, so we decided to wait to see what they would become...especially since we'd apparently already "contributed" our nest-(eggplant)egg! 🍆💜😅 

Some of the caterpillars didn't end up making cocoons, but settled down to pupate, while others spun lovely little cocoons. 

After about 40 days we found *this* moth which must have emerged from one of the cocoons.

1 - Dramatic front view
2 - Taking off
3 - A pink-bellied caterpillar on Simon's hand
4 - A non-cocooned papa wriggling a bit - "Hey, there's someone *in* here!"
5 - A cocoon swinging around on a silken thread
6 - Love the shadow - drama!
7 - Tail lift 😄
8 - Top view complete with woolly legwarmers
9 - The soft side
10 - Are we done yet?
11 - In the glass on the way out
12 - Underside showing the proboscis and trailing antennae
13 - Sadly a front leg was lost in transit...
14 - Nearly out!
15 - A pupa without a cocoon
16 - A cooon
17 - Another cocoon
18 - The moth on a bench just prior to flying off...goodbye!

Wanting to find out more about it, we used the Leucinodes genus as a starting point, and managed to find a close relative, Leucinodes laisalis or the Brown Tipped Pearl, which seems to be a beautiful match for this moth:
https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/782633-Leucinodes-laisalis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/782633-Leucinodes-laisalis/browse_photos. Thank you Garth Aiston and Suncana Bradley for confirming the ID for us 🙂

"It is mainly distributed in Africa, in Côte d’Ivoire, the Gambia, Ghana, Kenya, Morocco, Niger, Nigeria, Réunion, Senegal, South Africa and Tanzania. It has also been recorded in Belgium, Spain, Portugal and the United Kingdom, which probably do not represent native occurrences of the species but rather unintended introductions along with imports of tomatoes and other Solanaceae, the species' host plants.

"The larvae exclusively feed on the fruits of Solanaceae. Their recorded host plants are Solanum anguivi [forest bitterberry], Solanum incanum [thorn apple, bitter apple, bitterball or bitter tomato], Solanum linnaeanum [devil's apple], Solanum macrocarpon [African eggplant], Solanum melongena [eggplant, aubergine or brinjal], Lycopersicon esculentum [tomato] and Capsicum annuum [paprika, chili pepper, jalapeño, cayenne, bell pepper etc.]." 

Apparently it has also been reported on Syzygium cumini [Malabar plum, Java plum etc.] and Solanum aethiopicum [bitter tomato, Ethiopian eggplant or nakati] (https://africanmoths.com/pages/CRAMBIDAE/SPILOMELINAE/Leucinodes%20laisalis.html and https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38629305/).

[explanations inserted]

So it seems the caterpillars don't only have a taste for our eggplants 🍆 , but this kind of caterpillar seems to have a preference for *any* kind of eggplant, *and* a lot of pretty hot stuff as well! No wonder we found it able to chew its way through plastic with its "jaws of steel"...or is that jaws of "steal" 🤣! https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/301432695. 

Who would think those little pink bellies could become such elegant moths! 

Update: A little while later we found another moth had emerged from a cocoon: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/301454447.

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1B35jMYv2d

A little while ago (29 June 2025) we discovered these amazing green caterpillars on our Bronze Fennel.

Last year we found some bright yellow ones, apparently Fennel Moth Caterpillars, on the same Fennel in March here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/288164916 and in May here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/288170989.

These ones look quite different, so we thought we'd try to rear them to see what might emerge...

One of the caterpillars had already started to spin a cocoon, and after two further days (01 July 2025) the remaining caterpillars also did the same. 

One decided to spin its cocoon waaaay at the top of the water bottle we were keeping them in. 

Little by little the Fennel leaves dried out and the cocoons remained (Last three piccies from 07 July 2025).

What would emerge we wondered? 🤔  

Update: The moths subsequently emerged one by one, and we were delighted to discover that there was *gold* at the end of the emerald rainbow! 🌈🌞 

The first moth emerged on 24 July here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/302549697.

The second moth, that had cocooned at the mouth of the water bottle, emerged on the same day here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/302579743.

The third moth got its proboscis stuck in the pupal case and didn't eclose normally, but still became a little miracle moth 🥰🤗: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/302814272.

It looks as if this bee is possibly a Cape Honeybee or Cape Bee, Apis mellifera ssp. capensis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/429428-Apis-mellifera-capensis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/429428-Apis-mellifera-capensis/browse_photos,

The Cape Honeybee "is endemic to the Western Cape region of South Africa on the coastal side of the Cape Fold mountain range." When looking at the distribution maps on iNaturalist we seem to live in the Eastern end of the distribution of the Cape Honeybee, whereas the African Honeybee seems to occur nationwide so both subspecies could be expected to occur here in this region.

Apparently the Cape Honeybee "tends to be darker in colour than the African honey bee (A.m. scutellata) with an almost entirely black abdomen, this differentiates it from African honey bees which have a yellow band on the upper abdomen."

There is a lot more interesting information about this bee here: https://www.sanbi.org/animal-of-the-week/cape-honeybee.

description: Please correct my ID. On persimmon.

Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/178SdmLt3W

Lovely! 😋

It's always wonderful to see a tiny moth diving whole-heartedly into some flowery nectar! 😄

It's only about 8mm long.

This lovely little thing is possibly an Eccopsis cf. incultana (Tortricidae family): https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/663423-Eccopsis-incultana and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/663423-Eccopsis-incultana/browse_photos. Thanks so much for confirming this ID for us Quartus Grobler 🙂  

The plant is possibly a Fever Tea, Lippia cf. javanica (Verbenaceae family): https://pza.sanbi.org/lippia-javanica, https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/343067-Lippia-javanica and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/343067-Lippia-javanica/browse_photos.

"Common names: fever tea, lemon bush (English); koorsbossie, beukesbossie, lemoenbossie (Afrikaans); mutswane, umsutane (Swati); inzinziniba (Xhosa); umsuzwane, umswazi (Zulu); musukudu, bokhukhwane (Tswana)...

This 1 to 2 m high woody shrub stands erect and is multi-stemmed. The stems have a square appearance when looked at in cross-section. The leaves are hairy with noticeable veins and when crushed gives off a strong lemon-like smell. It is said to be one of the most aromatic of South Africa's indigenous shrubs. The small cream flowers can be found on the shrub from summer to autumn in some areas and in others are produced all year. These flowers are arranged in dense, rounded flower heads. The fruit are rather inconspicuous, small and dry...

Lippia was named after Augustin Lippi 1678- 1701, an Italian traveller and natural historian who was killed in Abysinnia. This plant also occurs in Java, hence the epiphet javanica, meaning 'from Java'."

description:
With Don Fraser. The weather at the start was sunny and 76 degrees ("feels like" 76), with a light breeze. I counted the following butterflies, mostly on the blooming Bristle Thistles: 68 swallowtails, 69 skippers, 7 sulphurs, and 1 Gulf Fritillary. This was the day that I learned that Larger Florida Mantises are killing machines, something I had wondered about in 2023, as the numbers of skippers declined through the fall season. Don and I watched one mantis capture and consume one Twin-spot Skipper (1024-1035) and then immediately capture and eat a second Twin-spot Skipper (1037-1041), then capture and consume a third Twin-spot Skipper (1055-1108), and then instantly start hunting a Palmetto Skipper, which escaped at the last possible milli-second, and then try to capture a Palamedes Swallowtail, which also escaped at the last milli-second. I did not enjoy watching the killing sequences, but I did not intervene at all. We left here at 1122 (after 2 hours!) and headed to Scrub Island Road.

I NEED TO ADD MY REMAINING CAMERA PHOTOGRAPHS AND THEN COMBINE PHONE + CAMERA PHOTOS REPRESENTING THE SAME RECORD.

description:
Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/19co5sgLP4

©️ This is a duplicate in part of the Tortoise Beetle post here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/308202105.

And there are the munch marks! 😃

According to Hugh Heron: "From the photograph, the morning glory looks to be Ipomoea cairica. This is an important host plant for a number of tortoise beetles: from my records, at least nine of our species reproduce on it (ten if we include this observation)." Thanks Hugh! 🙂

That's certainly very interesting! These Morning Glories are certainly absolutely everywhere around here 🙂

We see this one is called the Mile-a-minute Vine, Ipomoea cairica: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/77494-Ipomoea-cairica and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/77494-Ipomoea-cairica/browse_photos. Thanks for confirming the ID for us miaunt and Alexis López Hernández 🙂

"Ipomoea cairica is a vining, herbaceous, perennial plant with palmate leaves and large, showy white to lavender flowers. A species of morning glory, it has many common names, including mile-a-minute vine, Messina creeper, Cairo morning glory, coast morning glory and railroad creeper. The species name cairica translates to 'from Cairo', the city where this species was first collected...

The vine blooms occasionally throughout the months, but more profusely from spring to summer.

Its exact native range is uncertain, though it is believed to originate from a rather wide area, ranging from Cape Verde to the Arabian Peninsula, including northern Africa, tropical Africa and the Mediterranean. It covers walls, fences or trees, with stems that can measure more than 10 metres in length. The altitude at which it has been recorded ranges from 250 metres to 2,250 metres.

Because of human dispersal, it occurs today on most continents as an introduced species and is sometimes a noxious weed and an invasive species, such as along the coast of New South Wales...

Some plant nurseries sell this plant as an ornamental plant thanks to its showy purple flowers and as well for its fast growth to quickly cover unsightly fences or walls. It can grow as a separate plant if snapped during attempted removal process. The plant causes respiratory symptoms if ingested.

Ipomoea cairica 'alba', also known as 'white Cairo morning glory', is a variety with white flowers.

Most parts of the plant are edible, such as its leaves, which are eaten when young. And its roots, which can be cooked prior to eating. Zulu people use the plant medicinally, where they make a concoction with its crushed leaves and drink it to heal rashes and fever. The plant in some areas is also considered to have antibiotic properties."

What a fascinating plant! And what a wonderful host to all these precious beetles 🥰🙂

description: Sidewinder Trail - Little Bennett Regional Park
Juvenile Western Gull with prey. All those crabs on the beach and he chose to take the crayfish out of the tiny freshwater pond.

Quoting from the original Facebook post containing additional video 🎥 footage: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/1DB7FBkPuV

Fascinating...

On 16 July we discovered these rather peculiar-looking larvae on a plant (separately posted here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/309463126) in the park. 

From some previous discussions with Suncana Bradley we knew that these aren't caterpillars, but more likely Sawfly larvae.

Intrigued we collected a few for rearing along with a few cuttings from the plant...

Unfortunately the cuttings were rather woody and kept wilting even though put them in water, so we kept returning to gather more cuttings until we became concerned that we'd be pruning the plant too far and on 20 July we rather returned the larvae to what was left of the bush 😊

While we were doing so we spotted a really laaarge larva (just over 25mm long) that looked as if it might nearly be ready to pupate, so we collected it along with another small cutting and placed it into a container.

We had read that Sawflies tend to drop to the soil in order to pupate, so we filled the bottom of the container with soil.

The chubby little larva munched and munched as you can see in the second and third videos (see Facebook link above) and on 25 July it dropped to the bottom of the container to pupate in the soil.

We found that quite amazing, so after another two days we carefully dug it up to see what it looks like and then returned it back into the soil.

The wait was on...what, if anything, would come out of that beautiful little cocoon we wondered? 🤔  

Edit1: According to Simon van Noort the plant is possibly a member of the Camphorbushes, Tarchonanthus sp.: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/474040-Tarchonanthus and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&preferred_place_id=6986&taxon_id=474040&view=species. That's very helpful, thanks Simon! 🙂 

Update: After a tense month of misting the soil and watching what would happen, we're very happy to announce the arrival of a very special little one 🧡🖤🤗: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/309649273.

It looks as if it's possibly an Arge whiteheadi: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1631502-Arge-whiteheadi and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/1631502-Arge-whiteheadi/browse_photos.

Edit2: We subsequently sent messages to both Andreas Taeger and Simon van Noort telling them the good news about the arrival of the little one.

Andreas replied that: "It's interesting to see this successful rearing, even if the host plant is not safely identified.

The photos of the female leave for me no doubt that this is A. whiteheadi. It seems to me rather unlikely that there is "doppelganger"."

So this little one is evidently also a little lady - thanks so much Andreas! 🙂

Simon also helpfully confirmed the ID. Thanks Simon! 🙂

It's possibly the larva of a South African Fool's Gold Beetle, Aspidimorpha quadriremis: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/567886-Aspidimorpha-quadriremis and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/567886-Aspidimorpha-quadriremis/browse_photos. Thanks for the ID confirmation Hugh Heron.

description: This observation is to ID the bee
Fungal infection on the leaves and fruit of a common pawpaw tree (Asimina triloba).

One of the coolest caterpillars I've ever found! I was suspicious that the host plant might be a stinging nettle, so I used a tissue to grab the leaf and turn it over for photos. A separate observation of the host plant can be seen here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/310867962

The algorithm has suggested Question Mark and Eastern Comma, which would make sense if I've ID'd the host plant correctly as a nettle.
This crow was eating a pigeon, though it's not clear how the pigeon died

Quoting from the original Facebook post: https://www.facebook.com/share/p/16twHprjqD

Any idea what this spidey caught? 🤔

The spider is possibly a Baryphas ahenus Jumping Spider: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/464010-Baryphas-ahenus and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/464010-Baryphas-ahenus/browse_photos. Thanks for confirming this ID Rudi Steenkamp 🙂

⚠️🚧🚫
Edit1: Perhaps, as suggested by Jessica Myburg and Jan Botha, the bug is a True Bug and possibly a Plant Bug (Miridae family): https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/53505-Miridae and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&taxon_id=53505&view=species. Thanks Jessica and Jan! 🙂

Looking through some of our previous records this certainly looks like a possibility since we have previously found greenish ones e.g. here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/311014304 here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/311013314 and here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/311011277, and a yellowish one here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/311008426.
⚠️🚧🚫

Edit2: Fascinatingly enough Dawid Jacobs took a look at this bug and commented that "The last antennal segment seems to be short and thick - something not present or at least not common in the Miridae. I think this may be a coreid but the photo is not clear enough to be sure." Wow! Quite some forensics happening with this little bug - thanks so much Dawid - we really appreciate you contributing your insight there! 🙂

So according to Dawid the knobble at the end of this bug's antennae indicate that this bug is more likely to be a member of the Pentatomomorph Bugs: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/372868-Pentatomomorpha and https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=6986&preferred_place_id=6986&taxon_id=372868&view=species. Thanks also Johan Pretorius for confirming this ID 🙂

🌍 Wooooow! Really? 🤔

This little butterfly recently swooped past us and then disappeared, *poof*

We couldn't find it anywhere, but look where it went! 👀

Who would have guessed it, apparently even the butterflies love mielie sap "nectar" as we found to be the case with wasps, for example here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/297821544, here https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/297801241 and here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/297200091.

🌍 There are also some ants 🐜 (separately posted here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/312403738) enjoying a good meal.

Edit: Steve Woodhall commented about this observation: "That is very interesting. Ants and wasps (and butterflies of course) are known to be attracted to sugary things like leaking plant sap. That maize plant appears to be under fungal attack (the whitish matter the butterfly is sucking on). That would make it leak sap. It could also be a site where something (like a beetle grub or Corn Borer moth larva) is penetrating the stem, causing a sap leak which then ferments and the smell attracts the other insects. This is a well known phenomenon on trees and shrubs and Bush Browns are known for attending such feeding sites. I'm not sure this is the same as them sucking grass seeds (or flowers) though. For a start, there would be very little sap in those whereas in a big mealie stem, plenty! I read one theory that the grass seeds were under attack by an ergot fungus which also produces sugars and it's that that's the attraction. The Joker I photographed on Sorghum was clearly sucking a liquid (that's the first time I've seen liquid involved on a grass). This would benefit from some proper scientific investigation. I don't have the resources to investigate this very far, it would need a powerful microscope, a medium for growing fungal cultures etc.) I might try taste but I'm a bit reluctant to risk that if ergot is involved. That can be a very toxic fungus! And insects can withstand toxins we can't. Ergot is where lysergic acid comes from, the psychoactive ingredient in LSD." 

Wow, very interesting 🙂 You're right about the damage...we saw that here, where a Fruit Chafer was chomping at a stalk - it seems to have set the picnic table for a whole host of bugs: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/312405980.

We also recently saw a Green Shield Bug doing the same sort of "damage" thing and ants coming for the opening here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/283633460.

Aside from that, the sticky, gooey, fungally stuff that forms after rain is also quite an attractant as we saw here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/312416716 

here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/312425600

and even more here: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/312431170.

Who would have thought there would be so much more to these plants! 🌽Positively popping 🍿 with life! 😍

Thanks for taking the time to share your thoughts, it's amazing what we find out there!

From a previous post we found this to be a Black-haired Bush Brown with the wonderful name Bicyclus safitza safitza 🚴‍♂️🚴‍♀️ : https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/312383477.

So this is apparently a Bush Brown Bicyclus, safitza ssp. safitza: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/340019-Bicyclus-safitza-safitza and https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/340019-Bicyclus-safitza-safitza/browse_photos. Thanks for confirming the ID for us Fanie Rautenbach 🙂

description: White-M hairstreak flew into Spotted Orbweaver's web and was eaten over the next hour.

It was being carried around by a Maroon-legged Lion Fly (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/314042040), and dead by the time the photos were taken.
Possibly roadkill? Found in a parking lot
